Repo: /Users/aipalm/.local/share/nx01/w/r516ac04a9285/fa265b8ab039e/A1/repo. Current HEAD already contains your prior `Job.max_runs(n)` implementation plus a SURFACE_CLOSE docstring fix. Authorized surface unchanged: `schedule/__init__.py`, `test_schedule.py`.

Two independent VERIFY judges (a primary broad-coverage judge and an adversarial pair judge) reviewed your diff against `.devlyn/criteria.generated.md`. Both are CONFIRMED real via direct execution (not speculation) — you must fix both.

## Finding 1 (HIGH, confirmed) — extra execution when budget is lowered after some runs already happened

`Job.run()` only checks the run-budget AFTER `job_func()` executes (`self.run_count += 1` then `if self._max_runs is not None and self.run_count >= self._max_runs: return CancelJob`). There is no pre-execution guard. Repro (already executed, real output):

```
job = every().second.max_runs(5).do(job_fn)
job.run()                    # run_count=1, in scheduler.jobs
job.max_runs(1)              # last-call-wins: budget lowered to 1 (already met/exceeded)
scheduler.run_all()          # BUG: job_fn is called a SECOND time (call_count=2) before cancellation
```

This violates the criteria's Requirement: "After the job has executed n times in total, the job removes itself... The nth execution itself still runs normally; an (n+1)-th execution must never happen." Since the job already executed once and the budget was then set to 1, the very next scheduler-driven run IS the (n+1)-th execution relative to the current budget, and it must not happen.

**Required fix**: add a pre-execution guard mirroring the existing `.until()` pattern in the same method — `Job.run()` already has `if self._is_overdue(datetime.datetime.now()): return CancelJob` at the very top (before calling `job_func()`), which guards against a job that's already overdue. Add an equivalent pre-execution budget guard right next to it (same place, before `job_func()` is called): if `self._max_runs is not None and self.run_count >= self._max_runs`, return `CancelJob` immediately without calling `job_func()`. Keep the existing post-execution check as-is (it's still needed for the normal nth-execution-then-cancel path). Do not change anything else about the control flow.

Verify your fix against the exact repro above (a throwaway check is fine, not a tracked file) — after the fix, `call_count` must stay `1` and the job must not be in `scheduler.jobs` after the `run_all()` call, since `.max_runs(1)` was set after the job already ran once.

## Finding 2 (MEDIUM, verdict-binding, confirmed) — ScheduleValueError does not satisfy "raises ValueError"

The criteria's literal Requirement: "n must be an integer >= 1; any other value raises ValueError at `.max_runs(...)` call time." Your implementation raises `ScheduleValueError`, but `ScheduleValueError(ScheduleError)` does NOT subclass the built-in `ValueError` — confirmed via `issubclass(schedule.ScheduleValueError, ValueError)` returning `False`. A caller doing `except ValueError:` around `.max_runs(bad_value)` will NOT catch it.

**Required fix (root cause, not a workaround)**: change the `ScheduleValueError` class declaration itself to also inherit from the built-in `ValueError`, e.g. `class ScheduleValueError(ScheduleError, ValueError):` (multiple inheritance — already confirmed to produce a clean MRO with no conflicts: `ScheduleValueError -> ScheduleError -> ValueError -> Exception -> BaseException -> object`). This is a one-line change to the existing class declaration in `schedule/__init__.py`. Do NOT raise a bare `ValueError` instead of `ScheduleValueError` anywhere — that would break the codebase's existing `ScheduleValueError`-based catches and tests (`.until()`, `.at()`, etc.). The multiple-inheritance fix satisfies the literal spec requirement for `max_runs()` while preserving `ScheduleValueError` as the raised type everywhere else in the file, unchanged.

After this fix, `every().max_runs(0)` (or any invalid value) must raise something that is BOTH `isinstance(exc, ValueError)` and `isinstance(exc, schedule.ScheduleValueError)` True.

## Also (LOW, optional but recommended — closes the coverage gap that let Finding 1 slip through)

Add one regression test in `test_schedule.py` for the Finding 1 scenario (lower `.max_runs()` after the job has already executed at least once; assert no extra execution happens and the job is removed). Add or extend an assertion that the raised exception for invalid `n` is an instance of the built-in `ValueError` (not just `ScheduleValueError`), e.g. `self.assertRaises(ValueError, every().max_runs, 0)` alongside the existing `ScheduleValueError` assertions — do not remove the existing `ScheduleValueError` assertions, just add `ValueError` coverage since both should now hold.

## Constraints

- Files not in the authorized surface (`schedule/__init__.py`, `test_schedule.py`) are off-limits.
